I'm using SQLite feature only.

When my invocation of query method failed with DatabaseError such as primary key constraint error, resource monitor shows a core of CPU is occupied 100% and not released until my application is terminated.

When I inserted a manual invocation of PoolConnection::release in error handling code, this problem ceased. But, is this pattern expected by design?

```rust
    {
        let mut conn = pool.acquire().await?;
        if let Err(err) = sqlx::query("INSERT INTO objects ( id, message ) VALUES ( ?1, ?2 )")
            .bind(1) // may trigger constraint error
            .bind("hello")
            .execute(&mut conn)
            .await
        {
            conn.release(); // required for releasing a core
            println!("Error: {}", err);
            println!("Continue..");
        }
    }
```

Additionally, this pattern cannot be applied on Pool directly since Pool does not have release method.
